value.title: Reps. Paul Gosar, Andy Biggs credited in video with organizing Trump crowd in DC on day of riot
value.excerpt: The man who has led the "Stop the Steal" protests nationally singles out Reps. Paul Gosar and Andy Biggs for helping make Washington gathering happen.

value.title: Forbes editor issues warning to companies intending to hire Trump officials: 'We'll assume everything you talk about is a lie'
value.excerpt: The editor of Forbes magazine has warned companies not to hire Kellyanne Conway, Sean Spicer, Kayleigh McEnany, Stephanie Grisham, or Sarah Sanders.

value.title: Google, Microsoft, Verizon on Biden Inauguration Committee donor list
value.excerpt: Google, Microsoft, and Verizon are among President-elect Joe Biden's Inauguration Committee donors.

value.title: Trump speech before Capitol riot not enough for impeachment charges: Turley
value.excerpt: Democrats are moving to remove President Trump from office after Wednesday's U.S. Capitol riot, but George Washington University law professor Jonathan Turley said he doesn’t believe Trump committed an impeachable offense.

value.title: Mulvaney: Earlier Trump controversies were 'policy differences' or 'stylistic,' but 'Wednesday was existential'
value.excerpt: Former White House chief of staff Mick Mulvaney, who resigned as envoy to Northern Ireland over President Trump’s handling of the deadly riot at the U.S.

value.title: Vogue's Kamala Harris cover sparks social-media frenzy: 'What a mess up'
value.excerpt: The cover of February's upcoming issue of Vogue, which features Vice-President-elect Kamala Harris, has been widely criticized on social media.

value.title: Nancy Pelosi, in ‘60 Minutes’ interview, slams Trump as ‘deranged,’ calls for ‘prosecution’
value.excerpt: President Trump is "deranged, unhinged, dangerous," and deserving of prosecution, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi says in an interview scheduled to air Sunday night on "60 Minutes."

value.title: Trump to visit U.S.-Mexico border to laud border wall

value.title: Top Republican says Trump committed 'impeachable offenses'
value.excerpt: Democrats' momentum for a fresh drive to quickly impeach outgoing President Donald Trump has gained support, and a top Republican said the president's role in the deadly riot at the Capitol by a violent mob of Trump supporters was worthy of rebuke.

value.title: Pence will attend Biden's inauguration
value.excerpt: Vice President Mike Pence will attend the inauguration of President-elect Joe Biden, according to a source familiar.

value.title: Mediaite: Parler CEO says it took down post from Lin Wood calling for Mike Pence's execution
value.excerpt: The CEO of Parler, a social media platform popular among conservatives, told Mediaite that it removed a post from attorney Lin Wood calling for Vice President Mike Pence to be executed by "firing squads."

value.title: Pence has not ruled out 25th Amendment, source says
value.excerpt: Vice President Mike Pence has not ruled out an effort to invoke the 25th Amendment and wants to preserve the option in case President Donald Trump becomes more unstable, a source close to the vice president says.

value.title: GOP Sen. Toomey: Trump 'committed impeachable offenses'
value.excerpt: Republican Sen. Pat Toomey, Pa., said that President Trump “committed impeachable offenses” in his efforts to throw out the results of the 2020 presidential election.

value.title: Republican Sen. Pat Toomey says he thinks Trump 'committed impeachable offenses'
value.excerpt: Republican Sen. Pat Toomey of Pennsylvania said Saturday he thinks President Donald Trump "committed impeachable offenses," but said he is not certain attempting to remove the President from office with just a few days left in his term is the right course of action.

value.title: Trump considering Giuliani and Dershowitz for impeachment defense team
value.excerpt: Staring down the barrel of a second impeachment, President Donald Trump is beginning to mull who would represent him in a Senate trial.

value.title: Trump Twitter ban will be ‘exploited’ by ‘enemies' of free speech 'around the world,’ Russian dissident Navaln
value.excerpt: Russian opposition leader Alexey Navalny called Twitter’s ban of President Trump an “unacceptable act of censorship” that could be exploited by oppressive governments around the world.

value.title: House Dem apologizing for comparing new Trump impeachment to a 'lynching'
value.excerpt: An Oregon Democrat is apologizing for likening a second impeachment of President Trump to a "lynching."

value.title: Donald Trump Jr.: ‘We are living Orwell’s 1984’ after dad outed from Twitter
value.excerpt: Free-speech no longer exists in America. It died with big tech and what’s left is only there for a chosen few. This is absolute insanity!” he tweeted in response to the news.

value.title: If Biden halts border wall, it could cost taxpayers billions, CBP chief warns
value.excerpt: President-elect Joe Biden is promising that border wall building won't continue under his administration, but with hundreds of miles under construction, the head of Customs and Border Protection (CBP) is warning that shutting down construction could cost taxpayers billions.

value.title: House could vote to impeach Trump on Wednesday, one week after Capitol protest turned into a mob
value.excerpt: As the country comes to terms with the violent siege of the U.S. Capitol by Trump supporters that left five dead, the crisis that appears to be among the final acts of his presidency is deepening like few others in the nation’s history.

value.excerpt: The topic trended briefly, with many people quoting Trump supporters who invaded the Capitol Wednesday chanting the phrase, as a noose awaited outside.

value.title: Brit Hume: Twitter's reasons for banning Trump are 'pure editorial judgments'
value.excerpt: Fox News Senior Political Analyst Brit Hume is calling out big social media companies for making the decision to ban President Trump's accounts based on what he says are "pure editorial judgments."

value.title: Former Goldman Sachs CEO Lloyd Blankfein slams Wall Street traders as Trump enablers
value.excerpt: Lloyd Blankfein said Wall Street put up with Trump because of what he could deliver, which was mainly lower corporate taxes and fewer regulations.
